.NET Core is missing suitable APIs for dealing with filesystems that contain symbolic links

FileInfo does not resolve symbolic links, leading to subtle bugs. There's no API that gives information about the link target. There's other problems with the existing APIs causing them to have trouble when you call Directory.EnumerateFileSystemEntries involving having to do not one but two stat calls for each node. Might as well resolve them all at once.

Proposed API surface:

    // These are deliberately set to the *nix constant values where possible.
    public enum FileTypes {
          Missing = 0,
          Fifo = 0010000,
          CharacterDevice = 0020000,
          Directory = 0040000,
          BlockDevice = 0060000,
          File = 010000,
          SymbolicLink = 0120000,
          Socket = 0140000,
          ReparsePoint = 0200000, // ReparsePoint attribute set but not a symbolic link
    }

    public struct FileNode {
        public string Path { get; private set; }
        public string FileName { get => System.IO.Path.GetFileName(Path); }
        public DateTime LastAccessTime { get; private set; }
        public DateTime LastAccessTimeUTC { get; private set; }
        public DateTime LastWriteTime { get; private set; }
        public DateTime LastWriteTimeUTC { get; private set; }
        public DateTime LastChangeTime { get; private set; }
        public DateTime LastChangeTimeUTC { get; private set; }
        public FileAttributes Attributes { get; private set; }
        public FileTypes FileNodeType { get; private set; }
        public string ReadLink(); /* call the appropriate API */
        public bool Exists { get => FileNodeType != 0 }
        FileNode(string path, bool resolvesymboliclink)
        {
                /* The general idea of this API is it doesn't throw; just gives the appropriate information You could probably put Cer.Success on it. */
                Path = path;
                bool statpermissiondenied;
                if (resolvesymboliclink)
                {
                    /* This code path would call CreateFile with only FILE_READ_ATTRIBUTES and then call GetFileInformationByHandle; on AccessDenied or PermissionDenied fall through below */
                    /* on unix this would be a stat() call */
                }
                /* This code path would call FindFirstFileEx to get the file information by name from the node attribute */
                if (resolvesymboliclink && FileNodeType == FileTypes.SymbolicLink)
                   FileNodeType = 0;
        }
        /* Deserialization constructor */
        FileNode(string path, FileTypes fileNodeType, FileAttributes Attributes, DateTime lastAccessTimeUTC, DateTime lastChangeTimeUTC, DateTime lastWriteTimeUTC);
    }

    public partial class File {
         public static void CreateSymbolicLink(string target, string link, bool targetisdirectory = false);
    }


    public partial class Directory {
         // This one exists only code readability
         // The idea is the programmer would normally only pass the third parameter if it was indirection from another layer of indirection, and otherwise would call File.CreateSymbolicLink to create a symbolic link to a file and Directory.CreateSymbolicLink to create a symbolic link to a directory
         public static void CreateSymbolicLink(string target, string link, bool targetisdirectory = true)
                => File.CreateSymbolicLink(target, link, targetisdirectory);
    }

I'm experimenting with using SignalR to dynamically inject html and Typescript generated ES into pages. Getting the info into the pages works fine, but "registering" the content is hanging me up. For example, I am injecting fragments of html (a set of form fields) into a page, and I want to interact with the elements in the partial, including invoking SignalR. 

## Background

With a page and section,
```
<div id="container">
    ...
    <div id="formFields" ></div>
    ...
</div>
```
when the page loads, it requests some default fields. Other field sets are requested when running.
```
    connection.start().then(() => {connection.invoke("GetFields", "default")}
```
The hub event handler sends the content.
```
public class PageHub : Hub {
    public async void GetFields(string fieldset) {
        // fieldset == "default"
        string content = $@"
       <input type="text" id="name" />
       <input type="text" id="age" />
        ";
        
        await Clients.Client(Context.ConnectionId).InvokeAsync("FillFields", content );
    }
}
```
On the client, SR adds the fields to the page.
```
// Typescript
const find = (id: string): Node => document.getElementById(id);
connection.on("FillFields", content: string ): void {
        const section = find("formFields") as HTMLDivElement;
        section.innerHTML = content;
```
As long as the page is anticipating/expecting specific content, I can prepare/declare, and access the info in Typescript/ES. In a TS class I can expose the fields as properties, and use them in my client code. This code is in a TS class in the page from the beginning. 
```
const findInput = (id: string): HTMLInputElement => document.getElementById(id) as HTMLInputElement;
const reader = (formField: HTMLInputElement) => formField.value; // ...null handlers not shown
const writer = (formField: HTMLInputElement, value: string) => formField.value = value;

    private readonly Name_ = findInput("name");
    get name(): string { return reader(this.Name_); }
    set name(value: string) { writer(this.Name_, value); }

    private readonly Age_ = findInput("age");
    get name(): string { return reader(this.Age_); }
    set name(value: string) { writer(this.Age_, value); }
```
The reader/writer handle cases where the items aren't present.

## Problem
The example is not much more than a very complex show/hide, since the page must know what fields might be present, and have code for them. A problem is that inserted code doesn't get "registered" with the page. For example, if I insert a button and button handler, they don't get bound. Here I inject a fragment with a button and handler. 
```
<button id="submit">Press Me</button>
<script>  
    const submit_ = document.getElementById("submit");

    function register() {
        submit_.addEventListener("click", (e) => submitHandler(e), true);
    }
</script>
```
I need to run the `register` function to bind the handler. An approach I considered was using SR to run a "binding function". In the code I inject, I could also inject a `connection.on`, and call that.
```
<button id="submit">Press Me</button>
<script>  
    const submit_ = document.getElementById("submit");

    function register() {
        submit_.addEventListener("click", (e) => submitHandler(e), true);
    }

    connection.on("bindEvents", () => { register();  });
</script>
```
Sending the `connection.on("bindEvents")` has the same problem - it wouldn't be registered. I'll get a `Not Found`  if I try:
```
    Clients.Client(Context.ConnectionId).InvokeAsync("bindEvents");
```  
## Solution
It would be nice to be able to add "on events" from server-side. Using something like an `AddEvent` method. This would have an overload that would create and map the event.
```
Clients.Client(Context.ConnectionId).AddEvent("bindEvents");
Clients.Client(Context.ConnectionId).AddEvent("bindEvents", ()=>{ } );

```
With this capability we can create some very dynamic pages.
```
// My Page
<html>
<head>
    <script src="~/signalr/hubs"></script>
</head>
<body>
    <div id="dynamicBody" ></div>
</body>
<script>
    var connection = new signalR.HubConnection("/pageHub");
    connection.start().then(()=>{
        connection.invoke("Startup");
    });
    
    connection.on("InitPage", content: string ) {
       const body= document.getElementById("dynamicBody");
       body.innerHTML = content;
   }

</script>

// Server
public class PageHub : Hub {
   void Startup(){
      string content = $@"
         connection.on("initialize", () => { "init" }
         function init () {
         // All of the script and html for the page, generate dynamically
         // ...
      }";
      Clients.Client(Context.ConnectionId).InvokeAsync("InitPage", content);
      Clients.Client(Context.ConnectionId).AddEvent("initialize");
      Clients.Client(Context.ConnectionId).InvokeAsync("initialize");
   }
}
```

